"2010-07-20T20:09:05.667"	"2"	"76"	"As for the utility of inner product spaces: They're vector spaces where notions like the length of a vector and the angle between two vectors are available. In this way, they generalize R^n but preserve some of its additional structure that comes on top of it being a vector space. Familiar friends like Cauchy-Schwartz, the parallelogram rule, and orthogonality all work in inner product spaces.\r\n\r\nThe dot product is the standard inner product on R^n. In general, any symmetric, positive definite matrix will give you an inner product on C^n. And you can have inner products on infinite dimensional vector spaces, like \r\n\r\n$\\int_a^b \\! f(x)g(x) \\, dx$\r\n\r\nfor f, g square-integrable functions on [a,b].\r\n\r\nThis becomes useful, for example, in applications like Fourier series where you want a basis of orthonormal functions for some function space (it's not just the trigonometric functions that work)."	"ff165336-76f0-466d-8c65-cfdca91c73c9"	"86"	"155"	""	""	""
