"2010-07-20T20:11:12.370"	"2"	"72"	"Note that if you replace i, j, and k with m, n, and p, the determinant becomes the dot-product of the vector (m, n, p) with the cross-product of the two original vectors.  If (m, n, p) = (a, b, c) or (m, n, p) = (d, e, f), the determinant is zero (any matrix with two identical rows has determinant zero), so the dot product of (a, b, c) or (d, e, f) with the cross-product is zero.  Hence, (a, b, c) and (d, e, f) are orthogonal to their cross-product."	"1ab49198-67c8-4a40-b47c-b1be767b9351"	"89"	"160"	""	""	""
