"2010-07-20T20:48:24.463"	"2"	"72"	"![diagram][1]\r\n\r\nThe field is the smaller/left circle, centered at A.  The cow is tied to the post at E.  The larger/right circle is the grazing radius.  Let the radius of the field be R and the length of the rope be L.\r\n\r\nThe grazable area is the union of a segment of the circular field and a segment of the circle defined by the rope length.  (A segment of a circle is a sector of a circle less the triangle defined by the center of the circle and the endpoints of the arc.)  The area of a segment of a circle of radius r with central angle &theta; is 1/2 * R^2 * (&theta; - sin(&theta;)), where &theta; is measured in radians.\r\n\r\nIn order to express the grazable area in terms of L and R, we need expressions for the measures of &ang;CED and &ang;CAD (which define the segments of the circles; call these &alpha; and &beta; for convenience).  By using the Law of Cosines on the blue triangle in the diagram, &alpha; = m&ang;CED = 2 * arccos( L / (2 * R) ) and &beta; = m&ang;CAD = 2 * arccos( (2 * R^2 - L^2) / (2 * R^2) ).\r\n\r\nThe grazable area is 1/2 * L^2 * (&alpha; - sin(&alpha;)) + 1/2 * R^2 * (&beta; - sin(&beta;)).  We want that to be equal to half the area of the field, 1/2 * &pi; * R^2.\r\n\r\nThat is, the relationship between L and R is 1/2 * L^2 * (2 * arccos( L / (2 * R) ) - sin(2 * arccos( L / (2 * R) ))) + 1/2 * R^2 * (2 * arccos( (2 * R^2 - L^2) / (2 * R^2) ) - sin(2 * arccos( (2 * R^2 - L^2) / (2 * R^2) ))) = 1/2 * &pi; * R^2.\r\n\r\n![equation][2]\r\n\r\nThere is no algebraic method of solving this equation for L in terms of R (Mathematica cannot `Solve[]` or `Reduce[]` it).\r\n\r\n\r\n  [1]: http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4098/4813477804_c0da66060a.jpg\r\n  [2]: http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4093/4812853421_f6dcdc7982.jpg"	"fe78bbb7-896a-4b47-b6cd-db8f2a0b282f"	"109"	"210"	""	""	""
"2010-07-20T20:48:39.627"	"2"	"92"	"The argument against this is that 0.99999999... is ""somewhat"" less than 1. How much exactly?\r\n\r\n          1 - 0.999999... = \u03b5\r\n\r\nIf the above is true, the following also must be true:\r\n\r\n    9 \xd7 (1 - 0.999999...) = \u03b5 \xd7 9\r\n\r\nLet's calculate:\r\n\r\n    0.999... \xd7\r\n    9        =\r\n    -----------\r\n    8.1\r\n      81\r\n       81\r\n         .\r\n          .\r\n           .\r\n\r\n    -----------\r\n    8.999...\r\n\r\nThus:\r\n\r\n         9 - 8.999999... = 9\u03b5              (1)\r\n\r\nBut:\r\n\r\n             8.999999... = 8 + 0.99999...  (2)\r\n\r\nIndeed:\r\n\r\n    8.00000000... +\r\n    0.99999999... =\r\n    ---------------\r\n    8.99999999...\r\n\r\nNow let's see what we can deduce from `(1)` and `(2)`.\r\n\r\n    9 - 8.999999... = 9\u03b5\r\n    9 - 8.999999... = 9 - (8 + 0.99999...) =\r\n                    = 9 -  8 - (1 - \u03b5)\r\n                    =   1    -  1 + \u03b5\r\n                    =               \u03b5.\r\n\r\nThus:\r\n\r\n    9\u03b5 = \u03b5\r\n\r\n    10\u03b5 = 0\r\n\r\n    \u03b5 = 0\r\n\r\n    1 - 0.999999... = \u03b5 = 0\r\n\r\nQuod erat dimostrandum. Pardon my unicode."	"3496be11-6fc2-41c7-91ac-b91c6ae2f2a5"	"110"	"211"	""	""	""
