"2010-07-20T21:42:02.833"	"2"	"51"	"Exponents are only ""basically"" defined under the natural numbers above zero.  By this I mean, defined as ""iterated multiplication"" the same way multiplication is defined as iterated addition.\r\n\r\nThe property `a^0 = 1` only arises when we look at generalizing multiplication to the integers.  We do this by:\r\n\r\n    a^4 / a^3 = (a*a*a*a)/(a*a*a) = a^1\r\n    a^4 / a^3 = a^(4-3)           = a^1\r\n\r\nAnd using this, we can say:\r\n\r\n    a^2 / a^3 = a^(-1) = 1/a\r\n\r\nand also:\r\n\r\n    a^2 / a^2                 = 1\r\n    a^2 / a^2 = a^(2-2) = a^0 = 1\r\n\r\nSo we say `a^0 = 1`.\r\n\r\nHowever, notice that these proofs don't have any meaning when `a=0`, because the whole concept/idea involves fractions, and you cannot have zero be in the denominator.\r\n\r\nWhen we say `2^0 = 1`, we really mean:\r\n\r\n    2^(1-1) = 2^1 / 2^1 = 2/2 = 1\r\n\r\nBut we cannot say the same for `0^0`:\r\n\r\n    0^(1-1) = 0^1/0^1 = 0/0 = UNDEFINED\r\n"	"0ab30108-3170-4e47-b070-061fb631b99b"	"144"	"278"	""	""	""
