"2010-07-20T21:44:28.357"	"5"	"536"	"A nonsingular projective curve of genus 1, which is an abelian variety under the group law: basially, this means that you   draw the line through two points on the curve -- which can be embedded in the projective plane -- and find where that line intersects the curve again (and call that the negative of the sum).  We can always put elliptic curves in the (projectivization of the) form $y^2 = x^3 - Ax + b$.  So you can add points on the elliptic curve, which is really cool; there isn't a way to do this for most objects in algebraic geometry.  Then one can study things like the torsion points on an elliptic curve, with respect to this abelian group structure: it's a theorem that there are $m^2$ torsion points of order $m$ for instance, if you 're working in an algebraically closed field.  In fact, one way to think of this is that an elliptic curve is really a torus if you are working over the complex numbers, and the torsion points in the torus are easily determined. This also yields the theorem for algebraically closed fields of characteristic zero via the ""Lefschetz principle.""  (For characteristic p, you need a different argument.)  That's a bit about elliptic curves; I know nothing about cryptography and can't comment on that."	"979bd344-e7cb-46a1-ade8-3d5d06ee0317"	"137"	"282"	"added 839 characters in body"	""	""
