"2010-07-20T23:22:46.597"	"5"	"67"	"Take a pair of compasses and draw an arc between two opposite corners, centred at another corner, and then draw a diagonal across the arc. If you now draw two lines from the point of intersection, parallel to the sides of the square, the biggest resulting square will have half the area of the original square."	"78e05170-b51b-45d4-abba-3fcf643b1bff"	"146"	"352"	"added 9 characters in body"	""	""
"2010-07-20T23:27:10.833"	"2"	"73"	"![alt text][1]\r\n\r\n[Dan's][2] algebraic justification is correct, but you may get more intuition about why this is happening from the above picture. Each time you want to enlarge the square by one unit, you have to add an extra row, an extra column, and one more square to fill in the corner. These correspond directly to the $n+n+1=2n+1$ that Dan mentioned. And of course, $2n+1$ is how odd numbers look.\r\n\r\n\r\n  [1]: http://www.education.vic.gov.au/images/content/studentlearning/mathscontinuum/SquareNos_sml.gif\r\n  [2]: http://math.stackexchange.com/questions/136/why-are-the-differences-between-consecutive-squares-equal-to-the-sequence-of-odd/143#143"	"665e79b9-13ce-4a41-8337-58317d28752a"	"183"	"353"	""	""	""
