"2010-07-21T01:23:22.517"	"2"	"73"	"I am no economist, so I can't speak about most of those conditions, but a reason I can see twice-differentiable as a reasonable requirement for a utility function to be 'well-behaved' is because the derivative of the utility function is marginal utility, and economists often care about the derivative of marginal utility. For example, if the second derivative of utility is negative, this means that the marginal utility has a negative derivative in other words, additional quantity of the good or service does not add utility as quickly. Also commonly referred to as diminishing returns.\r\n"	"598fbaa2-3924-4786-a5cc-bcc5b5c54b6f"	"226"	"435"	""	""	""
