"2010-07-21T05:12:52.277"	"2"	"122"	"The [Monty Hall problem][1] fits the bill pretty well. Almost everyone, including most mathematicians, answered it wrong on their first try, and some took a lot of convincing before they agreed with the correct answer.\r\n\r\nIt's also very easy to explain it to people.\r\n\r\n\r\n  [1]: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monty_Hall_problem"	"0a5b6dc7-cc3c-4df0-9c48-5c2416f3bebd"	"258"	"550"	""	""	""
"2010-07-21T05:12:52.277"	"16"	"-1"	""	"0a5b6dc7-cc3c-4df0-9c48-5c2416f3bebd"	"258"	"551"	""	""	""
"2010-07-21T05:13:12.447"	"2"	"145"	"Let's group the terms as follows:\r\n\r\ngroup 1: 1/1                       (1 term) \r\n\r\ngroup 2: 1/2 + 1/3                 (2 terms)\r\n\r\ngroup 3: 1/4 + 1/5 + 1/6 + 1/7     (4 terms) \r\n\r\ngroup 4: 1/8 + 1/9 + ... + 1/15    (16 terms) \r\n\r\n. \r\n\r\n. \r\n\r\n.\r\n\r\nIn general, group n contains 2^n terms.  But also, notice that the smallest element in group n is larger than 1/2^(n+1).  For example all elements in group 2 are larger than 1/2^2.  So the sum of the terms in each group is larger than 2^n * 1/2^(n+1) =  1/2.  Since there are infinitely many groups, and the sum in each group is larger than 1/2, it follows that the total sum is infinite.  \r\n\r\n"	"4e2a2f73-b4f5-44e2-8f00-8c8fd7d64364"	"259"	"552"	""	""	""
