"2010-07-21T07:45:16.050"	"5"	"76"	"As for the utility of inner product spaces: They're vector spaces where notions like the length of a vector and the angle between two vectors are available. In this way, they generalize R^n but preserve some of its additional structure that comes on top of it being a vector space. Familiar friends like Cauchy-Schwartz, the parallelogram rule, and orthogonality all work in inner product spaces.\r\n\r\n(Note that there is a more general class of spaces, normed spaces, where notions of length make sense always, but an inner product cannot necessarily be defined.)\r\n\r\nThe dot product is the standard inner product on R^n. In general, any symmetric, positive definite matrix will give you an inner product on C^n. And you can have inner products on infinite dimensional vector spaces, like \r\n\r\n$\\int_a^b \\! f(x)g(x) \\, dx$\r\n\r\nfor f, g square-integrable functions on [a,b].\r\n\r\nThis becomes useful, for example, in applications like Fourier series where you want a basis of orthonormal functions for some function space (it's not just the trigonometric functions that work)."	"3c735621-3aa8-4ac1-be0f-ba1435525a8e"	"86"	"632"	"added 166 characters in body"	""	""
