"2010-07-21T12:27:04.667"	"2"	"536"	"If one has a homomorphism of two rings $R, S$, and $R$ has an identity, then the identity must be mapped to an idempotent element of $S$, because the equation $x^2=x$ is preserved under homomorphisms.  Now $5$ is not an idempotent element in $Z_{15}$, so the map generated by $1 \\to 5$ is not a homomorphism.\r\n\r\nHowever, 10 is an idempotent element of $Z_{15}$. In particular, the subring $T \\subset Z_{10}$ generated by 10 has unit 10.  Since it is annihilated by 3, and consequently by 18, there is a unital homomorphism $Z_{18} \\to T$ (i.e., mapping 1 to 10).  So your second map is a legitimate homomorphism of rings (composing with the injection $T \\to R$).\r\n\r\nBasically, the point of this answer is to check that one of your maps preserves the relations of the two rings, while the other doesn't.\r\n\r\n"	"ac37697a-8a95-4d27-9e9d-9a51f0909e80"	"310"	"706"	""	""	""
