"2010-07-21T12:46:15.347"	"2"	"120"	"One of the simplest is the series for arctangent:\r\n\r\ntan<sup>-1</sup> x = x - x<sup>3</sup>/3 + x<sup>5</sup>/5 - x<sup>7</sup>/7 ...\r\n\r\n&pi;/4 = tan<sup>-1</sup> 1, but that converges slowly.\r\n\r\nYou can use the [addition formula for the tangent][1] (tan (a+b) = (tan a + tan b) / (1 - tan a tan b)) to break down &pi;/4  to the sum of two angles and repeat; this can be used to come up with values for the arctangent that are smaller than 1 and therefore converge faster.\r\n\r\nexercise for the reader: show that &pi;/4 = 2 tan<sup>-1</sup> 2/11 + 3 tan<sup>-1</sup> 1/7\r\n\r\nThis then means that  &pi; = 8 tan<sup>-1</sup> 2/11 + 12 tan<sup>-1</sup> 1/7\r\n\r\nUse the arctangent formula with only a few terms and you will have pi to quite a few decimal places. (3 terms yields 3.14160, 4 terms yields 3.1415924, 5 terms yields 3.1415926592)\r\n  [1]: http://mathworld.wolfram.com/TrigonometricAdditionFormulas.html"	"2317c082-760a-4980-a300-91d0ad743041"	"315"	"714"	""	""	""
