"2010-07-21T12:59:08.067"	"2"	"173"	"A lot of people have mentioned Binet's formula.  But I suspect this is not the most practical way to compute the nth Fibonacci number for large n, because it requires either having a very accurate value of sqrt(5) and carrying around lots of decimal places (if you want to do floating-point arithmetic) or expanding large powers of (1+sqrt(5)) using the binomial formula.  The latter comes out to writing the Fibonacci number as a sum of binomial coefficients.\r\n\r\nThe following formulas hold, though:\r\nF(2n-1) = F(n)^2 + F(n-1)^2\r\nF(2n) = (2*F(n-1) + F(n)) F(n)\r\nwhich you can find derivations of in <a href=""http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_number"">the Wikipedia article on Fibonacci numbers</a>.  This lets you find F(k), for any k even or odd, in terms of two Fibonacci numbers with approximately half the index.  The result is faster than Binet's formula.\r\n"	"04b3df2a-9744-4a5a-a18a-bb7093648432"	"319"	"723"	""	""	""
"2010-07-21T13:00:49.560"	"2"	"89"	"to show that (p-1)! &equiv; -1 (mod p) without explicitly use group theory, maybe the simplest path is: (the following assumes p is odd, but if p=2 then the result is immediate)\r\n\r\n 1. given n &ne; 0, all values n, 2n, ... (p-1)n are different mod p. Otherwise, if hn &equiv; kn (mod p) then (h-k)n &equiv; 0 (mod p) against the hyphotesis that p is prime.\r\n 2. this means that each n has an inverse mod p, that is for each n there is a m such that mn &equiv; 1 (mod p).\r\n 3. the equation x<sup>2</sup> &equiv; 1 (mod p) may be written as (x+1)(x-1) &equiv; 0 (mod p); therefore its only solutions are x &equiv; 1 (mod p) and x &equiv; -1 (mod p). For each other number n, an inverse m must exist (because of the pigeonhole principle) but m &ne; n.\r\n 4. we are nearly done. Let's couple every number from 2 to p-2 with its own inverse. Their product is 1 (mod p), so they don't count in the overall total. 1 does not count either; it remains just p-1, that is -1 (mod p) as requested.\r\n\r\n"	"7c75f472-5ff4-4f31-bcda-9c4518e593c6"	"320"	"724"	""	""	""
"2010-07-21T13:01:37.873"	"2"	"123"	"I will quote [Wikipedia][1] on the definition of a ring homomorphism.\r\n\r\n> More precisely, if R and S are rings,\r\n> then a ring homomorphism is a function\r\n> f : R \u2192 S such that[1]\r\n>\r\n> * f(a + b) = f(a) + f(b) for all a and b in R\r\n> * f(ab) = f(a) f(b) for all a and b in R\r\n> * f(1) = 1\r\n\r\nThe last requirement is being relaxed. We can then sub in our `f`, in this case `f(a1)=5a` or `f(a1)=10a` and see if these relations hold. Given that these are small, finite and well understood groups, the problem is easy to solve from here.\r\n\r\n  [1]: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_homomorphism"	"0371f8a3-00bb-42c6-8841-aa034719edc4"	"321"	"725"	""	""	""
