"2010-07-21T13:28:39.320"	"2"	"9"	"A unital homomorphism between rings R and S is a ring homomorphism that sends the identity element of R to the identity element of S.\r\n\r\nHomomorphisms (between objects in any algebraic category like groups, rings, vector spaces, etc.) preserve the algebraic structure, and if you want a map between rings with an identity element, it is natural to require this to preserve this element (since it satisfies unique properties)."	"807f1d6a-110a-450e-b61a-0d6a846320c3"	"330"	"748"	""	""	""
"2010-07-21T13:29:30.147"	"5"	"536"	"If one has a homomorphism of two rings $R, S$, and $R$ has an identity, then the identity must be mapped to an idempotent element of $S$, because the equation $x^2=x$ is preserved under homomorphisms.  Now $5$ is not an idempotent element in $Z_{15}$, so the map generated by $1 \\to 5$ is not a homomorphism.\r\n\r\nHowever, 10 is an idempotent element of $Z_{15}$. In particular, the subring $T \\subset Z_{15}$ generated by 10 has unit 10.  Since it is annihilated by 3, and consequently by 18, there is a unital homomorphism $Z_{18} \\to T$ (i.e., mapping 1 to 10).  So your second map is a legitimate homomorphism of rings (composing with the injection $T \\to Z_{15}$).\r\n\r\nBasically, the point of this answer is to check that one of your maps preserves the relations of the two rings, while the other doesn't.\r\n\r\n"	"0221d499-0756-4c89-a37f-10ff245939d6"	"310"	"749"	"added 5 characters in body"	""	""
