"2010-07-21T14:51:01.790"	"2"	"171"	"Note that if\r\n\r\n                    y = (1 - x^7) ^ (1/5)\r\n\r\nthen \r\n\r\n    (1 - y^5) ^ (1/7) = x\r\n\r\nThis means $(1-x^7)^{1/5}$ is the inverse function of $(1-x^5)^{1/7}$. In the graph, one will be the same as the other when reflected along the diagonal line y = x.\r\n\r\nAlso, both functions' range are (0, 1] in the domain [0, 1). Therefore, the area under the graph in [0, 1) will be the same for both functions:\r\n\r\n      1                      1\r\n      \u222b (1 - x^7)^(1/5) dx = \u222b (1 - y^5)^(1/7) dy\r\n      0                      0\r\n\r\nGrouping the two integrals yield the equation in the title."	"cf016c3b-2710-41fc-9c74-a80695cba7c0"	"345"	"775"	""	""	""
