"2010-07-21T22:48:13.517"	"2"	"128"	"This interesting pattern of derivatives involving sine and cosine is related to the fact that e^x is its own derivative and that e^(ix) = cos(x) + i*sin(x) ([Euler's Formula][1]).\r\n\r\nThese two facts are in some sense the math hiding behind Justin L's more physical explanation, which you might well find more intuitive.  \r\n\r\n  [1]: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler%27s_formula"	"5cb1cea8-f3b7-4c41-a62f-bcddedfbba5e"	"403"	"929"	""	""	""
"2010-07-21T23:03:36.737"	"2"	"8"	"One of the main ways that sine and cosine come up is as two solutions to the differential equation y'' = -y.  Why is this an important differential equation?  Well, by Newton's second law it's the differential equation that says ""the force is proportional and opposite to the position.""  For example, this is what happens with a spring!  Now that's a degree 2 diff eq so it has a 2-dimensional space of solutions.  How to pick a nice basis of that space?  Well one way would be to pick f and g such that f' = i f and g' = -i g.  However, that involves too many imaginary numbers, so another option is f' = -g, and g' = -f.\r\n\r\nThus if you're trying to find two functions which explain oscillatory motion you're naturally lead to picking functions that have f' = g, g' = -f, etc.\r\n\r\n(On the other hand it's totally unclear from this point of view why Sine and Cosine should have anything to do with triangles...)"	"b05f3280-12f1-4164-b1a8-78858c499cb2"	"404"	"930"	""	""	""
