"2010-07-22T01:00:59.263"	"2"	"72"	"The regular polygons that form the Platonic solids are those for which the measure of the interior angles, say &alpha; for convenience, is such that 3&alpha;<2&pi; (360 degrees) so that three (or more) of the polygons can be assembled around a vertex of the solid.\r\n\r\nRegular (equilateral) triangles have interior angles of measure &pi;/3 (60 degrees), so they can be assembled 3, 4, or 5 at a vertex (3 * &pi;/3 < 2&pi;, 4 * &pi;/3 < 2&pi;, 5 * &pi;/3 < 2&pi;), but not 6 (6 * &pi;/3 = 2&pi;--they tesselate the plane).\r\n\r\nRegular quadrilaterals (squares) have interior angles of measure &pi;/2 (90 degrees), so they can be assembled 3 at a vertex (3 * &pi;/2 < 2&pi;), but not 4 (4 * &pi;/2 = 2&pi;--they tesselate the plane).\r\n\r\nRegular pentagons have interior angles of measure 3&pi;/5 (108 degrees), so they can be assembled 3 at a vertex (3 * 3&pi;/5 < 2&pi;), but not 4 (4 * 3&pi;/5 > 2&pi;).\r\n\r\nRegular hexagons have interior angles of measure 2&pi;/3, so they cannot be assembled 3 at a vertex (3 * 2&pi;/3 = 2&pi;--they tesselate the plane).\r\n\r\nAny other regular polygon will have larger interior angles, so cannot be assembled into a regular solid."	"b82b1c96-90f0-4be5-b61f-e691c26a3a84"	"416"	"959"	""	""	""
